      <header class="pg-header">
        <p class="pg-eyebrow">Friday</p>
        <h1 class="pg-title">Frigg</h1>
        <p class="pg-subtitle">Norse goddess of fertility, marriage, and witchcraft</p>
      </header>

      <p>
        Every Friday on the Gregorian calendar honors a Norse goddess. Her name was <strong>Frigg</strong> (sometimes spelled Frige or Frigga), and she was worshiped across the Germanic and Scandinavian world for centuries before any of those peoples ever heard the name of Yahuah.
      </p>

      <h2>Who She Was</h2>

      <p>
        In Norse mythology, Frigg was the wife of Odin (also called Woden — the same Odin who gives us Wednesday). She was the goddess of marriage, motherhood, fertility, and the home. She was also a goddess of magic and divination, and her priestesses practiced a form of sorcery called <em>seiðr</em> — a witchcraft-like ritual that involved trance-states and prophesy.
      </p>

      <p>
        The Anglo-Saxons knew her as Frige. The Old English name for the day was <em>Frigedæg</em> — Frige's day. From there it became <em>Frigday</em>, and finally Friday. The Germanic peoples named the sixth day of their week after this goddess, and the name has been carried forward unchanged for more than a thousand years into every modern Western language.
      </p>

      <h2>Why It Matters</h2>

      <p>
        Most believers say "Friday" without giving it a second thought. But every time the word is spoken or written, it honors a goddess of magic and fertility worship — exactly the kind of practice Yahuah condemned in the strongest terms throughout the Tanakh.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-scripture">
        <span class="ref">Deuteronomy 18:10–12</span> — "There shall not be found among you any one that maketh his son or his daughter to pass through the fire, or that useth divination, or an observer of times, or an enchanter, or a witch, or a charmer, or a consulter with familiar spirits, or a wizard, or a necromancer. For all that do these things are an abomination unto Yahuah…"
      </div>

      <p>
        The seiðr witchcraft practiced in Frigg's name is precisely the kind of divination Yahuah lists as an abomination. And yet the name of the goddess who patronized that witchcraft is now baked into the English calendar so deeply that even faithful believers say it without thinking.
      </p>

      <h2>Two Clocks That Cannot Be Mixed</h2>

      <p>
        Here is where many believers stumble. They take a Roman day-name and try to lay it over Yahuah's calendar — as if the two systems were talking about the same thing. They are not.
      </p>

      <p>
        Listen to almost any sermon about the crucifixion and you will hear the same line: <em>"Christ died on a Friday."</em> <strong>This is the error.</strong> Friday is a Babylonian/Roman day named after a Norse goddess. It has nothing to do with Yahuah's reckoning of time. To say the Messiah died "on a Friday" is to take a heavenly event and pin it to a pagan label — mixing two clocks that were never meant to touch each other.
      </p>

      <p>
        Yahuah's clock runs on its own terms. The new moon is Day 1 of the month — a non-work day, though not a Sabbath. From there the days are counted: Day 2, Day 3, Day 4, and so on. The Sabbaths fall on Days 8, 15, 22, and 29. When the next new moon appears, the count resets and a new month begins. <strong>There is no Friday in this system. There is no Tuesday. There is no Wednesday.</strong> Yahuah's days are counted from the new moon He hung in the heavens — not from the names a pagan world stamped onto a continuous seven-day rotation.
      </p>

      <h2>What to Do With It</h2>

      <p>
        Knowing where the name "Friday" came from does not necessarily mean a believer must stop saying it — language is what it is, and most who use the word have no idea of its origin. But knowing the origin matters. It matters because the Roman/Gregorian calendar is layered with centuries of pagan honor written into the names of days and months that Yahuah's people now use without question.
      </p>

      <p>
        <strong>The bigger lesson is the one most believers never learn: Yahuah's clock and Babylon's clock are not the same clock.</strong> They run on different principles, mark different things, and were never designed to translate into each other. The faithful watch the heavens and let the new moon tell them what day it is. The world watches its phone and lets a goddess tell it what day it is. The two answers are as far apart as east is from west.
      </p>

      <div class="pg-pull">
        Friday is Frigg's day. The heavens know nothing about her. Yahuah's clock counts from the new moon He set in the firmament — not from the name a pagan world stamped onto its week.
      </div>

